 {"id":"bd-2pct","title":"DPOR algorithm: systematic schedule exploration","description":"# DPOR Algorithm Implementation

## Goal

Implement the core DPOR (Dynamic Partial Order Reduction) algorithm for systematically exploring distinct schedules.

## Background

DPOR is the state-of-the-art for exploring concurrent program schedules:
- Sound: explores at least one schedule per Mazurkiewicz equivalence class
- Complete: finds bugs if they exist in any schedule
- Efficient: prunes equivalent schedules

## Algorithm Overview

```
1. Execute program with initial schedule
2. While execution not complete:
   a. At each scheduling point, record the choice made
   b. Identify races: pairs of concurrent conflicting operations
   c. For each race (e1, e2):
      - Add alternative schedule to backtrack set
      - Alternative: schedule e2 before e1
3. When execution completes:
   a. Check invariants (oracles)
   b. Pop next schedule from backtrack set
   c. Restore state and continue from divergence point
4. Repeat until backtrack set empty
```

## Key Data Structures

### ExecutionTree
```rust
pub struct ExecutionTree {
    /// Root of the tree
    root: NodeId,

    /// All nodes
    nodes: HashMap<NodeId, ExecutionNode>,

    /// Current path through tree
    current_path: Vec<NodeId>,
}

pub struct ExecutionNode {
    /// Parent node
    parent: Option<NodeId>,

    /// Scheduling decision at this point
    decision: ScheduleDecision,

    /// Child nodes (alternative schedules)
    children: Vec<NodeId>,

    /// State checkpoint (for backtracking)
    checkpoint: Option<StateCheckpoint>,

    /// Whether this subtree is fully explored
    explored: bool,
}

pub struct ScheduleDecision {
    /// Tasks that were ready
    ready: Vec<TaskId>,

    /// Task that was chosen
    chosen: TaskId,

    /// Event that was executed
    event: Event,
}
```

### BacktrackSet
```rust
pub struct BacktrackSet {
    /// Pending alternative schedules to explore
    pending: VecDeque<BacktrackPoint>,
}

pub struct BacktrackPoint {
    /// Node in execution tree to backtrack to
    node: NodeId,

    /// Task to schedule instead
    alternative: TaskId,

    /// Why we're exploring this alternative
    reason: BacktrackReason,
}

pub enum BacktrackReason {
    /// Race between two operations
    Race { event1: EventId, event2: EventId },

    /// Random exploration
    Random,
}
```

### StateCheckpoint
```rust
pub struct StateCheckpoint {
    /// Serialized runtime state
    state_bytes: Vec<u8>,

    /// Vector clocks for all tasks
    vector_clocks: HashMap<TaskId, VectorClock>,

    /// Happens-before graph at this point
    hb_graph: HappensBeforeGraph,
}
```

## DPOR Variants

### Basic DPOR
Original algorithm. Sound but may explore redundant schedules.

### Source-DPOR
Only backtrack at the 'source' of a race:
```rust
fn source_dpor_backtrack(race: &Race, execution: &Execution) -> Option<BacktrackPoint> {
    // Find the last point before e2 where we could have scheduled something else
    let source = execution.last_scheduling_point_before(race.e2);
    if source.ready.contains(&race.e1.task) {
        Some(BacktrackPoint::new(source, race.e1.task))
    } else {
        None
    }
}
```

### Optimal DPOR
Provably minimal exploration. More complex bookkeeping.

Start with Source-DPOR (good balance of simplicity and efficiency).

